  "prompt": "Is there life on other planets? What is the latest discoveries/evidence to support or debunk the idea?",
  "response": "As of 2023, there's no definitive proof of life on other planets, but there are several promising developments:\n\nSupporting Evidence:\n1. Potential Habitable Environments\n- Mars: Evidence of past liquid water and organic molecules\n- Europa (Jupiter's moon): Subsurface liquid ocean\n- Enceladus (Saturn's moon): Hydrothermal vents and liquid water\n- Potential conditions for microbial life exist on these celestial bodies\n\n2. Exoplanet Discoveries\n- Thousands of planets discovered in \"habitable zones\"\n- Some planets have similar conditions to Earth\n- Some have water, organic compounds\n\n3. Recent Notable Discoveries\n- 2022: James Webb Telescope detected carbon molecules in exoplanet atmospheres\n- Potential biosignatures detected on Venus and Mars\n- Phosphine gas (potential biological indicator) found in Venus's atmosphere\n\nChallenges/Limitations:\n- No direct evidence of extraterrestrial life\n- Current technology limits deep space exploration\n- Defining \"life\" is complex\n- Extreme distances make comprehensive investigation difficult\n\nScientific Consensus:\n- High probability of microbial life existing somewhere\n- Low probability of intelligent life\n- Continued research and exploration ongoing\n\nWhile promising, current evidence remains circumstantial and inconclusive.",
